"1645","1610":"1610","1675":"1675","1673":"1673","1684":"1684","1640":"1640","04 Jun 1655":"4 juni 1655","1672":"1672","1660":"1660","1727":"1727","1636":"1636","Lock Lymm, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Corkaugh, County Donegal, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Donegal, County Donegal, Ierland","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cramond,Midlothian,Scotland":"Cramond, Midlothian, Schotland"},"en":{"1645–1673":"1645–1673","1640–1727":"1640–1727","1636–Female":"1636–Deceased","1672–1727":"1672–1727","1675–Male":"1675–Deceased","1610–1684":"1610–1684","1610–1660":"1610–1660","1645":"1645","1610":"1610","1675":"1675","1673":"1673","1684":"1684","1640":"1640","04 Jun 1655":"4 June 1655","1672":"1672","1660":"1660","1727":"1727","1636":"1636","Lock Lymm, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Corkaugh, County Donegal, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Donegal, County Donegal, Ireland","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cramond,Midlothian,Scotland":"Cramond, Midlothian, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Ding, Fatt, Tov, Yol, Yun.","Scottish and English: variant of   Lynn  .","Probably also an altered form of Dutch <b>Van der Lijn</b> (see   Vanderlinden  )."]},{"name":"Linn","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."]},{"name":"Lenn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Len  ."]},{"name":"Flynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Connor, Declan, Kieran, Aidan, Brigid, Cathal, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, John Patrick, Kiernan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Floinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Flann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘red(dish), ruddy’. There were families of this name in various parts of Ireland. This name has also been Anglicized as   Lindsay  .","English: from Middle English <i>Flin</i>, representing the Old Norse male personal name <i>Fleinn</i>."]},{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Lynn  ."]}]},{"name":"Linn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lynn","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David William Lynn Linn was born in 1645, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Andrew David Cameron Linn, was 35 and his mother, Ann Margaret Blair, was 35. He married Janet Thompson on 4 June 1655, in Cramond, Midlothian, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1673, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1645–1673":"1645–1673","1640–1727":"1640–1727","1636–Female":"1636–Surnud","1672–1727":"1672–1727","1675–Male":"1675–Surnud","1610–1684":"1610–1684","1610–1660":"1610–1660","1645":"1645","1610":"1610","1675":"1675","1673":"1673","1684":"1684